Life on the edge!
We hope that Jeff, Jeri, Atlas, and their fur babies NEVER need our products, but they have them “just in case” !

from @thisisironclad
•
Giving fear the middle finger.

In this episode, meet Jeff, a former Navy SEAL, and his wife, Jeri, a physician assistant, who move to Alaska to start a new life on their own homestead. 

Along with their team of sled dogs, Jeff and Jeri embark on a journey north of the Arctic Circle in pursuit of the Porcupine caribou herd to try and fill the freezer for the year.

New episodes every week.

node.text: Whether negligence is involved, or just a freak accident, we all know anything can happen on the water. The question is, will you be prepared to save a life? Could be an accident on your boat, a situation 50 miles offshore, or a problem that you just so happened to be first on the scene. Will you be ready? It’s something as mariners we all don’t think about as much as we should, and I’m here to raise awareness so you as the captain will be ready to save a life. We teamed up with @northamericanrescue and @pelicanprofessional to help provide all captains with the best and most affordable Qualified Captain Trauma Kit. It is specifically dialed in with the medical equipment you will need for when things go south. I treat these kits like an EPIRB. I don’t leave with out one whether it’s my boat, a friends boat, or a commercial boat. More information about the kits are on our website. Go check them out today, and always be prepared. Thank you @djstruntz @northamericanrescue and @pelicanprofessional to help make this happen. At the end of the day, we all want to have a good time and make it home safe. Have a great week everyone. #qualified #qualifiedcaptaintraumakits #beprepared #savealife #northamericanrescue #pelicancase #collobration

A thousand words…
By @theanchorpointpodcast
“The men and women who are on front lines of these wildfires across the nation are the ones deserving to be on the cover of @time magazine…

Especially the ones who do this for less than minimum wage in some states, have zero presumptive healthcare benefits, and are only formally acknowledged as firefighters after a line of duty death…

Not to mention the mental health consequences of the hardships endured by a majority of these men and women.

Last night, even a good friend of mine said, “People are spent, and are getting numb to losing”…

The fact of the matter is this: We have a desperate need for resources, a change in weather, and to retain what little resolve the men and women on the fire line have left…

A true indicator of how the desperate situation on the ground is can be captured, in it’s entirety, by this one photo from @maxwhittaker…

Between the #dixiefire and the #caldorfire - South Lake Tahoe has been evacuated, Portola has been evacuated, thousands have been displaced, hundreds of structures reduced to foundations, and almost 1,000,000 acres of prestigious forest have been decimated between just these two fires alone…

As I look to both the north and south of me, and all I see is raging columns of pyrocumulus clouds through a veil of grey - I can’t help but wonder if this is the “new normal”?

Maybe it is the “new normal”… 

But I genuinely worry about what the human (and mental) toll looks like when it’s all said and done.”

node.text:
@nardoctor on Improvised Junctionals

With up to 17.5% of potentially survivable deaths (Eastridge, et.al) on the battlefield occurring from junctional hemorrhage it is important to know how to apply a junctional. Commercially designed device like the SAM Junctional TQ, AAJT, JETT and CROC all have different pros and cons as well as significant user preference. Advantage is that they are dedicated built devices and some provide pelvic stabilization. Regardless of your preference everyone should know how to properly apply an improvised junctional. Reading this post won’t suffice, you have to get out and practice it regularly. 
.
There are many different methods to improvise a junctional, I’ll go over some universal basics. Check out @deployedmedicine for full length video and instructions. Similar steps for neck, axilla and groin and all may require some creativity. 
.
1- Pack the wound with hemostatic (gauze or X-Stat) if possible (you need to master this skill first). Remember to hold pressure after packing and don’t let up. At this point your best option may be to just hold pressure (if its effective) throughout the patient transport. 
.
2- For neck and axilla, secure hemostatic with tightly wrapped pressure dressing. Ensure you do not occlude both carotid arteries in the neck (one is fine). 
.
3- Secure a Pressure Delivery Device (PDD), this can be a water bottle like a Nalgene, lacrosse ball, SAM junctional puck, shoe, etc… and place in the inguinal crease (target is common femoral artery- find yours on yourself or your partner now). 
.
4- Link two tourniquets together and place around casualties’ hips (greater trochanters of femurs is target) and directly over the PDD. While ensuring PDD is stable, tighten windlass/ratchet with goal of eliminating distal pulse (check foot- dorsalis pedis or anterior tibial). 
.
5- Stabilize PDD/Junctional (get creative here). Use Ace wraps, Tac-wrap or anything on hand to reinforce the PDD so pressure continuous to be directed toward the artery. Carefully move patient during transport. FREQUENTLY recheck for bleeding. Transport ASAP. 
.
Post your comments, tips and tricks below. 
#tccc #stopthebleed

node.text:
🩸MASSIVE TRANSFUSIONS 🩸

 from @the_resuscitationist

MTP I was part of after a GSW to abdomen and chest. 

TOTAL: 51 units of PRBC/FFP/PLATELETS (no cryo available and no whole blood available)

BLEEDING = number 1 cause of preventable death in trauma. Specifically from extremities.

MASSIVE BLOOD TRANSFUSION:
--> historically defined as 10 units of PRBC (packed red blood cells) in 24H. Also, trauma associated severe hemorrhage score (TASH) of >16 =50% need MTP. Some say MTP if 3U of PRBC/ 1h. 

FLUID RESUSCITATION PRINCIPLES: 
1. Restore intravascular volume.
2. Maintain O2 carrying capacity. 
3. Correct coagulation derrangements.

LETHAL DIAMOND 💎💀= Hypothermia + Acidosis + Coagulopathy +Hypocalcemia 
.
HEMORRHAGE SITES: street, chest, pelvis, abdomen, retroperitoneal, thigh (holds ~2L).

WHOLE BLOOD = BEST!!! Please stop giving bleeding patients normal saline / LR.
NOTE:Most places do not have  this, so component therapy of PRBC, PLASMA, and PLATELETS.

PROPPR TRIAL:  ratio of 1:1:1 component therapy is best.

MTP STEPS: 
1. starts prehospital with recognition. Gain access. Large peripheral IV works well or IO lines which also take blood. Notify trauma team/blood bank.
2. Primary MARCH survey 
3. Start with PRBC warmed and infused (belmont, level1, or pressure bag). Emergency release type O- for women childbearing age or O-/+ older women and men.
4. Simultaneously hang platelets (room temp, not under pressure)
5. Give plasma with a 1:1:1 ratio to other blood products
6. Give TXA 2g IV if injury <3h. Don't have to give over 10min.
7. Give CALCIUM w/ 1st unit (citrate storage in prbc binds patients own calcium) 1g Ca chloride or 3g Ca glucinated and repeat after each ~4units.
8. Keep patient warm. Keep room or ambulance heated.
9. Place A-line, complete procedures, monitor urine output, electrolytes, blood gas, pain control. Consider CRYO.
10. TEG if available .
11. Get ABGs and monitor to look for hyperkalemia, hypoglycemia, acidosis

NOTE Central lines not always needed. Large peripheral IV or RIC work wonders. IO can be initial line. Can give blood IO, but not very fast.

BELMONT: 500mL/min @ >37C* have this primed and ready if MTP suspected.
